00:22:42,193 --> 00:22:48,838
So the idea of compassion comes under this whole business of generosity.

194
00:22:48,859 --> 00:22:51,241
And it's coming from the heart of wanting to help.

195
00:22:52,061 --> 00:22:52,883
And

196
00:22:53,740 --> 00:23:22,109
when you give it you see whatever you're giving in the scriptures it says you know there are three parts there's one part which what you are giving has been attained in a wholesome way so your money has been earned through a wholesome job or whatever and you're giving it without any hope of return without any consequence and you're giving it to somebody who is worthy of the gift so

197
00:23:23,930 --> 00:23:26,952
And this brings up the old question about people on the streets, you see.

198
00:23:27,614 --> 00:23:36,363
Well, if you know somebody is going to use your money for drugs and whatnot, then it's up to you whether you want to give it or not.

199
00:23:36,383 --> 00:23:40,527
But you can give it and make sure that they know what your intention is.

200
00:23:40,747 --> 00:23:44,029
This is to help you get night lodgings or food.

201
00:23:44,550 --> 00:23:46,393
What they do with it is their problem.

202
00:23:46,972 --> 00:23:50,477
It's like, you get yourself into all sorts of silly states.

203
00:23:53,730 --> 00:24:03,704
And generosity in the commentaries, this is not in the scriptures as such, as far as I know, but they point out that generosity itself is actually a path to liberation.

204
00:24:04,026 --> 00:24:12,317
Because every time you're generous, every time you're giving something without hope of return, you're actually renouncing something.

205
00:24:12,897 --> 00:24:15,461
Now the whole of the spiritual life is renunciation.

206
00:24:16,242 --> 00:24:18,685
The whole of it.

207
00:24:18,705 --> 00:24:20,008
The whole of the spiritual life is renunciation.

208
00:24:20,461 --> 00:24:24,424
And this renunciation, remember, isn't some sort of self-mortification.

209
00:24:24,444 --> 00:24:27,827
We don't have to end up in rags on the streets or something.

210
00:24:28,528 --> 00:24:40,059
It's letting go of these attachments, letting go of these relationships we have to things, to our money, to our possessions, and to people, and to our time.

211
00:24:40,480 --> 00:24:41,862
My time is for me.

212
00:24:43,603 --> 00:24:47,446
And when you offer that, when you offer your...

213
00:24:47,798 --> 00:24:55,886
some of your wealth and some of your time for the benefit of somebody else, what you're actually doing is saying, well, I'm not going to use this amount of money to make me happy.

214
00:24:55,906 --> 00:25:00,030
I'm not going to have to give up going to the Costa del Sol this summer.

215
00:25:01,211 --> 00:25:01,653
Or worse.

216
00:25:03,575 --> 00:25:10,701
And I could use this time to listen to heavy rock, but I'm going to help you paint the walls.

217
00:25:11,423 --> 00:25:17,028
So that sense of giving something also has this,

218
00:25:17,396 --> 00:25:45,852
basic thing about renunciation you see and all this is quite easy when you when you come from the position of gratitude so this gratitude is such a lovely mental state to develop and just at any time at any time of the day whatever you're experiencing having had that experience to say thank you

219
00:25:46,337 --> 00:25:58,297
Whether you've just eaten a cup of coffee at one of the coffee houses, or whether you've just had a meeting with a friend, or whether you've just been caught in the rain and you're soaking wet, say thank you.

220
00:25:59,700 --> 00:26:07,071
And it's this business of just recognising the little gifts that are given to us every day.

221
00:26:07,593 --> 00:26:12,800
Every day something happens which is just given without your asking.

222
00:26:13,777 --> 00:26:19,122
Even if it's only the level of the air that you breathe.

223
00:26:21,825 --> 00:26:23,886
It doesn't have to be there, does it?

224
00:26:23,906 --> 00:26:32,575
You can actually go down even to basic physical things to raise that sense of gratitude.

225
00:26:32,775 --> 00:26:36,638
And then the rest of it follows quite simply, quite easily, usually.

226
00:26:38,840 --> 00:26:41,943
So you have to be careful with this business of compassion.

227
00:26:42,515 --> 00:27:11,239
and again it's always to do with intention so as soon as you want to move to make sure your conscious intention is wholesome see sometimes we're not aware of subliminal stuff it pops up later you know one example I always give is you know like like here when if you make an offering here you see you you know this is for the benefit of other meditators who come here because everything everything you've received has already been paid for by past donations

228
00:27:11,708 --> 00:27:13,309
So this is for the benefit of others.

229
00:27:13,770 --> 00:27:18,417
And then when that's really filled your heart, that's when you let go of it.

230
00:27:18,738 --> 00:27:19,659
That's the point.

231
00:27:19,679 --> 00:27:22,804
Now that action is a habit.

232
00:27:22,983 --> 00:27:25,146
You're creating the habit of just giving.

233
00:27:26,108 --> 00:27:31,256
Remember there's that distinction between a desire and the empowerment of the desire.

234
00:27:31,576 --> 00:27:34,420
So it depends on the desire.

235
00:27:34,460 --> 00:27:39,807
And then of course once you've given it, you always get this little voice saying you are truly a very generous person.

236
00:27:40,565 --> 00:27:43,647
Oh, you know, too much, get some back.

237
00:27:43,667 --> 00:27:46,869
So as soon as you see that, you say, well, that's old martyry, you see.

238
00:27:47,250 --> 00:27:48,030
That wasn't me.

239
00:27:48,451 --> 00:27:50,753
That's just the old habits coming through.

240
00:27:51,673 --> 00:27:55,076
And so you've got to be careful not to be judgmental about that.

241
00:27:55,096 --> 00:27:58,780
See, I must be a horrible, terrible person because I can't give something purely.

242
00:27:59,461 --> 00:28:00,021
Because you did.

243
00:28:00,261 --> 00:28:05,566
You did give something purely.

244
00:28:05,886 --> 00:28:09,930
So these things are sort of constant in our lives, you know.

245
00:28:10,518 --> 00:28:12,880
People ask us for little favours here and there.

246
00:28:16,523 --> 00:28:31,558
I got on a bus a while back and I must have looked terrible or something because this person actually got up and gave me their seat.

247
00:28:32,640 --> 00:28:35,142
Well, I expected that in the 50s or the 60s.

248
00:28:35,782 --> 00:28:39,866
You don't expect anybody to get up for some old cognac.

249
00:28:40,285 --> 00:28:42,930
I thought, thank you very much.

250
00:28:46,616 --> 00:28:48,339
So, these little gifts.

251
00:28:50,683 --> 00:28:54,530
Now, the other ones, perfections, where are we?

252
00:29:11,150 --> 00:29:15,616
So it starts off with the perfection of giving, the perfection of morality.

253
00:29:16,278 --> 00:29:25,291
So remember that our ethics is the measure of our delusion or enlightenment.

254
00:29:25,492 --> 00:29:36,329
All these five training rules that we keep, not to kill living beings and not to take what is not freely given, remember those are really gross things.

255
00:29:36,647 --> 00:29:46,923
And our job is to really move towards a refinement of our conscience, a refinement of our behavior.

256
00:29:48,684 --> 00:29:53,992
And in a sense, that's what the Buddha was trying to do with this Vinaya for monks.

257
00:29:54,012 --> 00:29:59,961
He was trying to make it so that the behavior of his monastics were refined.

258
00:30:00,561 --> 00:30:03,605
He's got masses of rules, even on how to eat.

259
00:30:04,227 --> 00:30:06,250
We can't chapu-chapu or suru-suru.

260
00:30:07,241 --> 00:30:11,928
You know, chapu-chapu, and suru, so when you take a drink.

261
00:30:13,609 --> 00:30:18,174
All these little rules about, you know, about a certain dignified way of behaving.

262
00:30:19,355 --> 00:30:24,261
So sila here is better translated not as morality, they always do that.

263
00:30:24,281 --> 00:30:26,525
It's more like ethics, which is to do with relationship.

264
00:30:27,105 --> 00:30:29,208
And this relationship also is to do with things.

265
00:30:29,548 --> 00:30:31,191
See, that's why I keep going about doors.

266
00:30:32,112 --> 00:30:33,232
I mean, poor doors.

267
00:30:35,743 --> 00:30:37,506
They've suffered a lot in this place, I can tell you.

268
00:30:38,086 --> 00:30:43,633
So it's a case of recognizing that if we're gentle with doors, we're probably a bit more gentle with people.

269
00:30:44,394 --> 00:30:47,416
You know, when you go home, just watch how you kick the French door shut.

270
00:30:48,238 --> 00:30:49,579
You know, just catch yourself doing it.

271
00:30:50,881 --> 00:30:53,844
As you're sort of leaving it with your hands full, you give it a kick.

272
00:30:56,326 --> 00:30:59,230
Or put your pan down on top of the stove, you know, bang!

273
00:31:00,511 --> 00:31:02,493
As though you've got a grudge.

274
00:31:05,765 --> 00:31:08,088
So that's morality.

275
00:31:08,690 --> 00:31:09,991
Renunciation we've talked about.

276
00:31:10,451 --> 00:31:13,998
And this renunciation, remember, that's what we're trying to do.

277
00:31:14,057 --> 00:31:25,717
We're trying to see where our attachments are and slowly undermine them completely until we get to the end where our relationship to life is just radically different.

278
00:31:26,156 --> 00:31:29,021
When I say radically different, it's not as though we don't have

279
00:31:29,592 --> 00:31:31,494
you know, right relationship now.

280
00:31:31,715 --> 00:31:33,417
It's just that it begins to corrupt.

281
00:31:33,458 --> 00:31:34,840
We override it.

282
00:31:35,141 --> 00:31:36,083
We override it.

283
00:31:36,544 --> 00:31:41,050
So we take, for instance, our little grace before meals.

284
00:31:41,531 --> 00:31:43,194
And that gives us the right attitude.

285
00:31:43,434 --> 00:31:44,517
And we're eating the food.

286
00:31:45,057 --> 00:31:51,127
And there's always this little bit of override of wanting to indulge in the taste.

287
00:31:55,613 --> 00:32:00,220
I noticed today that a few people, many more than usual, went up for seconds.

288
00:32:02,702 --> 00:32:03,423
I won't say any more.

289
00:32:08,991 --> 00:32:09,393
Wisdom.

290
00:32:10,815 --> 00:32:19,547
Wisdom is mainly to do with what we've been talking about all week, the dependent origination, the three characteristics of existence.

291
00:32:20,429 --> 00:32:21,990
And remember, there's three levels of wisdom.

292
00:32:22,230 --> 00:32:25,536
There's the wisdom that you receive from listening

293
00:32:25,701 --> 00:32:54,492
and seeing, and then it becomes your own wisdom, it becomes your own, when you can actually express it to another, when you can explain Buddhist principles to other people, it's become your own intellectual property, you might say, see, but if somebody says to you, well, what is this dependent origination, you say, well, you better go and ask Bodhidharma, and it's still, it's not as though you've not understood it, but it's not been absorbed, it's not been actually masticated, and

294
00:32:54,692 --> 00:32:56,996
And turned into your own particular property.

295
00:32:57,557 --> 00:32:59,219
So that's where you want to get to really.

296
00:32:59,740 --> 00:33:00,220
You know.

297
00:33:00,240 --> 00:33:01,321
At an intellectual level.

298
00:33:01,761 --> 00:33:03,243
To be able to explain to yourself.

299
00:33:03,565 --> 00:33:04,066
Karma.

300
00:33:04,385 --> 00:33:05,426
Dependent origination.

301
00:33:07,851 --> 00:33:12,135
These characteristics of existence and so on.

302
00:33:12,155 --> 00:33:13,577
And then of course they become real.

303
00:33:13,719 --> 00:33:15,601
Because you actually experience them.

304
00:33:16,602 --> 00:33:19,425
And then they're coming right from the heart of experience.

305
00:33:22,730 --> 00:33:23,270
Energy.

306
00:33:23,290 --> 00:33:23,771
Energy.

307
00:33:24,375 --> 00:33:25,297
Right energy.

308
00:33:26,577 --> 00:33:28,740
It's right there also in the Eightfold Path energy.

309
00:33:29,681 --> 00:33:30,040
Effort.

310
00:33:30,561 --> 00:33:31,142
Commitment.

311
00:33:33,443 --> 00:33:34,345
Stability.

312
00:33:35,385 --> 00:33:36,346
Diligence.

313
00:33:36,626 --> 00:33:39,670
We've got masses of words for this sort of right effort.

314
00:33:39,750 --> 00:33:40,310
Zeal.

315
00:33:41,612 --> 00:33:45,375
Not giving up.

316
00:33:46,115 --> 00:33:46,656
Committed.

317
00:33:46,957 --> 00:33:49,578
That's what this means.

318
00:33:49,638 --> 00:33:52,922
It doesn't mean the energy to run around a bit.

319
00:33:52,942 --> 00:33:53,623
It's a sort of

320
00:33:54,058 --> 00:33:57,221
It's the energy you need for that commitment to the path.

321
00:34:01,546 --> 00:34:02,226
Resolution.

322
00:34:02,826 --> 00:34:05,890
So this is part of it, the resolution bit, the Adhitana.

323
00:34:06,691 --> 00:34:11,514
And that energy shades into these resolutions that we make.

324
00:34:11,534 --> 00:34:17,780
And resolutions only last just about for as long as you say them.

325
00:34:18,902 --> 00:34:20,844
So you've got to keep resolving.

326
00:34:21,443 --> 00:34:23,525
Every day you've got to resolve

327
00:34:24,248 --> 00:34:39,188
even in relationships, you know, this taking refuge in precepts, for instance, people who've committed themselves to the path, sometimes for a short time, a year, other times for life.

328
00:34:40,088 --> 00:34:43,632
And it's like you get the feeling, well, I've done it now, and that's it.

329
00:34:44,193 --> 00:34:45,275
No, it has to be constant.

330
00:34:45,536 --> 00:34:54,086
It's like a marriage or a relationship, but especially a marriage, you know, like once you've committed yourself,

331
00:34:54,472 --> 00:34:55,653
at the marriage ceremony.

332
00:34:55,673 --> 00:34:56,054
That's it.

333
00:34:56,474 --> 00:34:57,615
You can forget it now.

334
00:34:57,635 --> 00:35:10,353
And of course, what happens is the little destructive things that happen in relationships and all that build up and there's nowhere where it can be resolved.

335
00:35:10,373 --> 00:35:22,268
So for me, like the anniversary for somebody who's married is an occasion of forgiveness and re-establishing the sort of right relationship.

336
00:35:22,288 --> 00:35:23,550
If you don't do that, it just gets...

337
00:35:24,036 --> 00:35:53,132
wanders off the path and I remember saying this when I was I was asked to give a little talk and do little ceremonies for a friend at his marriage and I said I pointed out that you know the love we're talking about is an emotion I said you know sometimes you have a romantic emotion towards your partner sometimes you don't

338
00:35:54,056 --> 00:35:55,978
And sometimes you love them and sometimes you don't.

339
00:35:56,278 --> 00:36:00,864
But that's not the love which we're talking about when we're talking about a relationship.

340
00:36:01,304 --> 00:36:06,188
Whether it's between married people, a friendship, between parents and their child.

341
00:36:06,789 --> 00:36:09,052
It's a sort of commitment to the person.

342
00:36:10,414 --> 00:36:14,338
And the commitment is defined by the relationship you've made.

343
00:36:14,757 --> 00:36:19,422
So obviously for a parent it's that commitment of parenting and so on.

344
00:36:20,871 --> 00:36:23,233
And you've got to separate that out.

345
00:36:23,273 --> 00:36:24,695
And that's the resolution, you see.

346
00:36:24,835 --> 00:36:25,817
That's your commitment.

347
00:36:29,940 --> 00:36:31,061
Then there's loving kindness.

348
00:36:31,762 --> 00:36:33,063
And finally, equanimity.

349
00:36:33,784 --> 00:36:41,773
So equanimity, as I think pointed out when you first came, was arguably the most important of these qualities.

350
00:36:41,853 --> 00:36:48,820
Because what equanimity does is it stops all these things falling into their

351
00:36:49,070 --> 00:36:52,293
what's known as their near enemy, or better still, their subtle enemy.

352
00:36:52,733 --> 00:36:57,259
How love slips into attachment, compassion into grief, and so on and so forth.

353
00:36:58,300 --> 00:37:02,443
How, for instance, even courage can move into foolhardiness.

354
00:37:02,664 --> 00:37:03,606
That's his near energy.

355
00:37:03,666 --> 00:37:07,590
His obvious one is cowardice, but his near energy is foolhardiness.

356
00:37:08,010 --> 00:37:15,197
So you can see in that particular case a lack of wisdom, being a bit stupid about what you can do.

357
00:37:15,958 --> 00:37:18,081
So equanimity is...

358
00:37:18,297 --> 00:37:36,298
is meant to keep you at that, it's meant to be a sort of base underneath us, which is calm, steadiness of attention, a sort of recognition of what's happening, so that as soon as we come off into the near enemy, we're sort of aware of it.

359
00:37:36,318 --> 00:37:47,291
But if you're caught up in it, you see, if there's a sort of excitement, a sort of over-excitement into something, then the equanimity is lost.

360
00:37:47,980 --> 00:37:52,346
You're always coming off a deeper base of calmness.

361
00:37:52,405 --> 00:37:56,271
That's the idea of equanimity.

362
00:37:56,291 --> 00:37:59,394
And again, it's something we can develop.

363
00:38:00,096 --> 00:38:01,478
And it's obviously not easy.

364
00:38:02,498 --> 00:38:06,384
It's something that comes with just the practice of it.

365
00:38:07,065 --> 00:38:08,827
And the important thing is this stopping.

366
00:38:09,067 --> 00:38:10,409
I keep talking about stopping.

367
00:38:10,449 --> 00:38:12,291
I keep trying to do it myself, frankly.

368
00:38:12,891 --> 00:38:17,277
Just stop for a moment and just see the momentum

369
00:38:17,663 --> 00:38:19,764
What's in that momentum?

370
00:38:19,784 --> 00:38:21,987
Some of it's wholesome, some of it isn't.

371
00:38:22,829 --> 00:38:24,731
Some of it you have to wait until it passes.

372
00:38:24,971 --> 00:38:28,034
As the momentum drops, it begins to lose energy.

373
00:38:28,655 --> 00:38:31,097
That calm base arises just quite naturally.

374
00:38:31,559 --> 00:38:34,422
And out of that you get your next intention and off you go.

375
00:38:35,543 --> 00:38:41,409
So it really is this effort to just keep stopping as much as you can throughout in your daily life.

376
00:38:44,731 --> 00:38:49,295
So tomorrow we have this little celebration.

377
00:38:49,856 --> 00:38:54,900
It's really celebrating the anniversary of the founding of this place.

378
00:38:54,920 --> 00:39:00,666
But it also, I would like to point out, you'll hear me point out the Mahaji Sayadaw as well.

379
00:39:01,347 --> 00:39:08,394
So I'll offer an occasion for those people who have taken refuge in precepts to re-establish that commitment.

380
00:39:10,197 --> 00:39:13,320
And just in case somebody might be thinking of doing that,

381
00:39:13,603 --> 00:39:21,894
it's just very quickly, it really is finding your reference point.

382
00:39:23,336 --> 00:39:27,422
What is the fount which is giving meaning to the rest of your life, even to death?

383
00:39:30,025 --> 00:39:37,175
Is there something that you already have which is giving that a complete meaning to your life, from birth until death?

384
00:39:38,056 --> 00:39:40,539
And everything you're doing, day after day,

385
00:39:40,773 --> 00:39:44,938
And all the things in your spiritual portfolio.

386
00:39:44,958 --> 00:39:46,760
Are they all just disparate elements.

387
00:39:46,820 --> 00:39:47,802
Like in a roundabout.

388
00:39:47,822 --> 00:39:49,724
You're sort of jumping from a horse.

389
00:39:50,164 --> 00:39:50,945
Onto a camel.

390
00:39:52,668 --> 00:39:53,009
Or is it.

391
00:39:53,389 --> 00:39:55,251
Or are you actually right in the centre.

392
00:39:55,851 --> 00:39:56,693
Of that roundabout.

393
00:39:57,054 --> 00:39:58,195
And these things just come up.

394
00:39:58,635 --> 00:40:01,760
And you're always moving from the centre.

395
00:40:01,780 --> 00:40:02,860
You're not on the periphery.

396
00:40:02,880 --> 00:40:04,262
Just jumping from one to the other.

397
00:40:04,623 --> 00:40:07,626
So the idea of the spiritual path.

398
00:40:07,987 --> 00:40:09,550
Is that you do have this grounding.

399
00:40:09,710 --> 00:40:10,610
You know yourself.

400
00:40:11,114 --> 00:40:16,039
who is your basic contact point, your reference point.

401
00:40:16,059 --> 00:40:19,262
And in Buddhism we have these three.

402
00:40:19,362 --> 00:40:20,742
The first one is the Buddha himself.

403
00:40:21,324 --> 00:40:40,141
So the Buddha is both the historical figure, who is a teacher, he's taught us this particular path, he's the exemplar, he actually travelled it, he's not teaching it as some intellectual understanding that he's got through life, and he's an archetype in the sense that

404
00:40:40,612 --> 00:40:43,155
That path is true for all human beings.

405
00:40:43,675 --> 00:40:46,900
If you look at any spiritual tradition, it's always about renunciation.

406
00:40:47,101 --> 00:40:58,458
You know, look at all the saints, from the Desert Fathers to St. Francis, Mother Therese of Calcutta, all these people, you know, Gandhi, all these people are renunciates.

407
00:40:58,478 --> 00:40:59,498
I mean, that's the spiritual path.

408
00:40:59,900 --> 00:41:06,510
And also, the more lay people, like, who's the South African president?

409
00:41:06,670 --> 00:41:07,251
I forget his name.

410
00:41:09,293 --> 00:41:09,693
Mandala.

411
00:41:09,713 --> 00:41:10,315
Mandala, yeah, Mandala.

412
00:41:11,003 --> 00:41:13,204
Mandela, got it, Mandela.

413
00:41:13,385 --> 00:41:19,472
I mean, you know, he gave his life to this whole thing.

414
00:41:19,512 --> 00:41:22,175
I mean, he's a secular saint, you might say.

415
00:41:25,217 --> 00:41:27,639
So, in that sense, he's the archetype.

416
00:41:28,001 --> 00:41:31,965
But, of course, what we're really taking refuge in from a spiritual point of view is the Buddha within.

417
00:41:33,425 --> 00:41:39,913
We're putting a certain confidence that there is something in us which is seeking liberation and will be liberated.

418
00:41:40,518 --> 00:42:07,572
although the Buddha would, I don't think, make such an outlandish statement as I'm going to make, but I can't imagine it not being a spiritual, psychological imperative that everybody, in the end, must become fully liberated, because that's the trajectory everybody's on, even when they seem to be going the opposite way, even when they're sort of getting into murky waters and doing terrible things.

419
00:42:08,260 --> 00:42:12,306
They're always, if you ask them, they're always doing it for what they think is a good reason.

420
00:42:12,326 --> 00:42:14,449
I mean, these ISIL people, you know, lots of them.

421
00:42:14,969 --> 00:42:16,391
And it's always a twisted love.

422
00:42:16,452 --> 00:42:19,876
It's always a love for something, but it's just, it's off.

423
00:42:22,579 --> 00:42:27,286
And the Dharma is the teaching, which is also this practice, right?

424
00:42:27,306 --> 00:42:28,548
The teaching and the practice.

425
00:42:29,891 --> 00:42:37,862
And that's really where the foundation is, because it's the practice itself, which is...

426
00:42:38,112 --> 00:43:03,563
realizing the path for us from moment after moment and then the sangha is again traditionally those people who've experienced uh nibbana so they're witnesses to the buddha but uh his company you know when the buddha's asked what does he mean by right livelihood he says uh good companionship it's interesting that he doesn't say making money or

427
00:43:05,871 --> 00:43:08,193
going out and helping lepers.

428
00:43:10,135 --> 00:43:12,418
He doesn't define it in those terms.

429
00:43:12,438 --> 00:43:14,740
He just says it's good companionship.

430
00:43:14,920 --> 00:43:17,423
That's where you find your right livelihood.

431
00:43:17,664 --> 00:43:27,012
So in other words, when you want to do something and you find the right companions, then you have this momentum that forms.

432
00:43:28,353 --> 00:43:31,317
And in the doing, that becomes your livelihood.

433
00:43:31,878 --> 00:43:34,661
Perhaps it could be translated as lifestyle.

434
00:43:34,681 --> 00:43:35,001
I don't know.

435
00:43:36,652 --> 00:43:38,534
So that's what the three refuges are.

436
00:43:40,237 --> 00:43:41,838
And they become your reference point.

437
00:43:41,858 --> 00:43:42,641
That's what it means.

438
00:43:42,960 --> 00:43:47,807
And of course the training rules are just basically a platform where you just don't want to go.

439
00:43:48,389 --> 00:43:52,795
And of course we usually have problems with the last one.

440
00:43:53,054 --> 00:43:55,920
You know, I'll take drinks and drugs, that cloud of mine.

441
00:43:55,940 --> 00:43:56,760
You know, what's wrong with that?

442
00:43:57,521 --> 00:43:58,583
Glass of wine and all that.

443
00:43:59,664 --> 00:44:01,867
And really they are training rules.

444
00:44:02,228 --> 00:44:03,190
They're not commandments.

445
00:44:03,210 --> 00:44:05,353
They're not sort of absolute statements.

446
00:44:05,393 --> 00:44:06,034
Thou shalt not.

447
00:44:06,806 --> 00:44:10,130
It's just, if you want to go on the path, this is the way you train yourself.

448
00:44:10,710 --> 00:44:15,737
So, you know, it's up to the individual how they want to define these things for themselves.

449
00:44:15,757 --> 00:44:23,525
But ultimately, knowing, say, the effect of alcohol on the body anyway, you generally wouldn't want to do it.

450
00:44:26,789 --> 00:44:28,710
So, we've covered a bit of ground there.

451
00:44:29,972 --> 00:44:35,498
And I can only hope that you will continue with your practice

452
00:44:35,782 --> 00:44:54,634
that you will devote yourself to your self-betterment, that my words have been an encouragement and not a discouragement, and that you will attain full liberation sooner rather than later.

